[zero_shot][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][mmlu] sample 17/100 done id=mmlu_validation_206 prediction='Let\'s solve this step-by-step:\n\n(i) The statement "The \'I\' stands for independent" is correct. In ARIMA(p,d,q) models, the term \'I\' typically refers to the number of differencing applied to the data before estimating the model. This is because ARIMA models assume stationarity, which means the mean of the series should remain constant over time. If we apply more than one difference, the model becomes non-stationary, leading to issues like autocorrelation and heteroskedasticity.\n\n(ii) The statement "An ARIMA(p,1,q) model estimated on a series of logs of prices is equivalent to an ARIMA(p,0,q) model estimated on a set of continuously compounded returns" is incorrect. Logarithmic transformations do not preserve the order of integration or the stationarity of the series. Therefore, estimates from logarithms cannot be directly compared to those from continuous compounding returns.\n\n(iii) The statement "It is plausible for financial time series that the optimal value of d could be 2 or 3." is correct. In practice, the optimal value of d (the degree of differencing) depends on various factors such as the nature of the data, the presence of seasonality, and the' gold='A' correct=False
