[few_shot][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][mmlu] sample 34/100 done id=mmlu_validation_457 prediction="To solve this problem, we need to determine the maximum possible distance between two exits given that each exit is at least 6 km apart and the total distance between exits 41 and 50 is 100 km.\n\nLet's denote the number of exits as \\( n \\). Since each exit is at least 6 km apart, the minimum distance between any two exits can be calculated using the formula for the sum of the first \\( n-1 \\) natural numbers:\n\n\\[ \\text{Minimum Distance} = \\frac{(n-1)n}{2} \\]\n\nGiven that the total distance between exits 41 and 50 is 100 km, we have:\n\n\\[ \\frac{(n-1)n}{2} = 100 \\]\n\nSolving for \\( n \\):\n\n\\[ (n-1)n = 200 \\]\n\\[ n^2 - n - 200 = 0 \\]\n\nThis is a quadratic equation. We can solve it using the quadratic formula or by factoring. Let's try factoring:\n\n\\[ n^2 - n - 200 = (n - 20)(n + 10) = 0 \\]\n\nSo, \\( n =" gold='A' correct=False
