[few_shot][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][mmlu] sample 71/100 done id=mmlu_validation_1182 prediction='To determine whether the appellate court will likely uphold the trial court\'s ruling, we need to analyze each option carefully:\n\nA. No, because the complaint\'s allegations were detailed and specific.\n- This statement aligns with the appellate court\'s decision. The appellate court found that the complaint contained detailed allegations about the supervisor\'s behavior and actions, which supported the employer\'s claim of discrimination based on sex.\n\nB. No, because the employer moved for summary judgment on the basis that the woman was not credible, creating a factual dispute.\n- This statement also aligns with the appellate court\'s conclusion. The employer argued that the woman\'s allegations were not credible due to her past behavior, but the appellate court ruled that the evidence presented was sufficient to support the employer\'s case.\n\nC. Yes, because the woman\'s failure to respond to the summary-judgment motion means that there was no sworn affidavit to support her allegations and supporting documents.\n- This statement contradicts the appellate court\'s ruling. The appellate court found that the woman did have a sworn affidavit (the email correspondence) to support her claims, so she cannot be considered "not credible."\n\nD. Yes, because the woman\'s failure to respond to the summary-judgment motion was a default giving sufficient basis to grant the motion' gold='B' correct=False
