[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 7/100 start id=gsm8k_test_93
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 7/100 path 1/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 7/100 path 1/3 answer="To find out how fast Gerald can run the 400-meter hurdles, we first calculate Lee's improvement rate:\nLee took 38 - 2 = <<38-2=36>>36 seconds to complete the race compared to Gerald.\nGerald’s improvement was 36 / 38 = 90% of Gerald's original time.\nSo, Gerald's current time for the race is Gerald's initial time + (90% of Gerald's initial time) = 1.9 Gerald's initial time + 0.81 Gerald's initial time = 2.71 Gerald's initial time = 2.71 / 1.9 ≈ 1.38 Gerald's improved time for the race is Gerald's initial time + (10% of Gerald's initial time) = 1.38 + (0.1 × 1.38) = 1.41 Gerald's improved time for the race is approximately 1.41 Gerald's improved time for the race is approximately 1.41 seconds"
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 7/100 path 2/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 7/100 path 2/3 answer="First, we determine what Lee was capable of running before he started improving his speed due to his better diet. Since Lee could run the 400-meter hurdles two seconds quicker than Gerald, we subtract 2 seconds from Lee's time to find out how long it would take him to run the same distance at his original speed:\n\nTime for Lee to complete 400 meters (without improvement) - 2 seconds = 39 seconds\n\nNow, we know Lee's current time is 38 seconds. With his improved diet, which increased his speed by 10%, we calculate the new time:\n\nLee's current time + 10% of his original time = 38 seconds + (10/100) * 38 seconds = 38 seconds + 3.8 seconds = 41.8 seconds\n\nTherefore, Gerald can run the 400-meter hurdles at a speed of 41.8 seconds."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 7/100 path 3/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 7/100 path 3/3 answer="To find out how fast Gerald can run the 400-meter hurdles, we first need to determine Lee's running time in seconds. Since he can run the hurdles two seconds faster than Gerald, and Lee takes 38 seconds, we subtract two seconds from Lee's time:\n\n\\[ \\text{Lee's time} = 38 \\text{ seconds} - 2 \\text{ seconds} = 36 \\text{ seconds} \\]\n\nNow, we calculate what Gerald's running time would be if his speed had doubled because his diet improved by 10%:\n\n\\[ \\text{Gerald's original time} = \\frac{\\text{Lee's time}}{1 + \\text{improvement rate}} \\]\n\\[ \\text{Gerald's original time} = \\frac{36 \\text{ seconds}}{1 + 0.10} \\]\n\\[ \\text{Gerald's original time} = \\frac{36}{1.10} \\]\n\\[ \\text{Gerald's original time} = 33.636 \\text{ seconds} \\]\n\nSince Gerald increased his time by 10%, we multiply his original time by 1.10 to account for this increase:\n\n\\[ \\text{Gerald's current time} = \\text{Gerald's original time} \\times 1.10 \\]\n\\[ \\text{Gerald's current time} = 33.636 \\text{ seconds} \\times 1.10 \\]\n\\[ \\text{Gerald's current time} = 36.9996 \\text{ seconds} \\]\n\nRounding to one decimal place, Gerald can run the 400-meter hurdles at a speed of approximately **37** seconds."
