[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 14/100 path 2/3 answer="To find out the total number of crabs the three have together, we first need to determine how many crabs each person has:\n\n1. Bo has 40 crabs.\n2. Monic has 4 fewer crabs than Bo, so Monic has \\(40 - 4 = 36\\) crabs.\n3. Rani has ten more crabs than Monic, so Rani has \\(36 + 10 = 46\\) crabs.\n\nNow, let's calculate the total number of crabs they all have together:\n\n\\[ \\text{Total} = \\text{Bo's crabs} + \\text{Monic's crabs} + \\text{Rani's crabs} \\]\n\\[ \\text{Total} = 40 + 36 + 46 \\]\n\nAdding these up gives us:\n\\[ \\text{Total} = 122 \\]\n\nSo, the three have a total of 122 crabs together."
