[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 17/100 path 1/3 answer='First, we calculate how many cards Elaine had after collecting in each month:\n- After the first month, she had \\(20 \\times 3 = 60\\) cards (since she collected three times what she started with).\n- After the second month, she had \\(60 + 20 = 80\\) cards (added 20 cards from the previous month and 20 cards from the first month).\n- In the third month, she collected twice the combined number of cards from the first two months, so \\(80 \\times 2 = 160\\) cards.\n\nTo find out how many cards she has now in total:\n- Total cards = Cards after the first month + Cards after the second month + Cards after the third month\n- Total cards = \\(60 + 80 + 160\\)\n- Total cards = \\(200\\)\n\nTherefore, Elaine has \\(200\\) cards now in total.'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 17/100 path 2/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 17/100 path 2/3 answer='First, we calculate how many cards Elaine collected in the first month:\n3 times the initial number of cards (20) = <<3*20=60>>60 cards.\n\nThen, in the second month, she collected 20 fewer cards than in the first month:\n60 - 20 = <<60-20=40>>40 cards.\n\nIn the third month, she collected twice the combined number of cards from the first two months:\n60 + 40 = <<60+40=100>>100 cards.\n\nAdding all these up gives us the total number of cards she has now:\n20 (initial) + 60 (first month) + 40 (second month) + 100 (third month) = <<20+60+40+100=220>>220 cards.'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 17/100 path 3/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 17/100 path 3/3 answer="To find out how many Pokémon cards Elaine has now, we can break down the problem into steps:\n\n1. Initially, Elaine had 20 Pokémon cards.\n   This gives us our starting point.\n\n2. In the first month, she collected three times what she had at the start:\n   3 * 20 = 60 Pokémon cards.\n\n3. In the second month, she collected 20 fewer cards than she did in the first month:\n   60 - 20 = 40 Pokémon cards.\n\n4. In the third month, she collected twice the combined amount of cards from the first two months:\n   (60 + 40) * 2 = 2 * 100 = 200 Pokémon cards.\n\nNow, let's add up all the cards:\nInitial cards + First month cards + Second month cards + Third month cards.\n20 + 60 + 40 + 200 = 320 cards.\n\nSo, Elaine currently has 320 Pokémon cards."
