<<60+40=100>>100 cards.\n\nAdding all these up gives us the total number of cards she has now:\n20 (initial) + 60 (first month) + 40 (second month) + 100 (third month) = <<20+60+40+100=220>>220 cards.': 1, "To find out how many Pokémon cards Elaine has now, we can break down the problem into steps:\n\n1. Initially, Elaine had 20 Pokémon cards.\n   This gives us our starting point.\n\n2. In the first month, she collected three times what she had at the start:\n   3 * 20 = 60 Pokémon cards.\n\n3. In the second month, she collected 20 fewer cards than she did in the first month:\n   60 - 20 = 40 Pokémon cards.\n\n4. In the third month, she collected twice the combined amount of cards from the first two months:\n   (60 + 40) * 2 = 2 * 100 = 200 Pokémon cards.\n\nNow, let's add up all the cards:\nInitial cards + First month cards + Second month cards + Third month cards.\n20 + 60 + 40 + 200 = 320 cards.\n\nSo, Elaine currently has 320 Pokémon cards.": 1}
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 18/100 start id=gsm8k_test_206
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 18/100 path 1/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 18/100 path 1/3 answer="First, let's calculate how many kilometers Micheal rode in the first period:\n- He rode 5 times a week, so over 4 weeks, he rode \\(5 \\times 4 = 20\\) times.\n- Each time, he rode 25 kilometers, so he rode a total of \\(20 \\times 25 = 500\\) kilometers in the first period.\n\nNext, we'll calculate how many kilometers he rode in the second period:\n- He rides 2 times a week, so over 3 weeks, he rode \\(2 \\times 3 = 6\\) times.\n- Each time, he rode 60 kilometers, so he rode a total of \\(6 \\times 60 = 360\\) kilometers in the second period.\n\nNow, we can find out the total number of kilometers Michael rode in both periods:\n\nTotal distance = Distance in first period + Distance in second period\nTotal distance = \\(500 + 360\\)\nTotal distance = \\(860\\) kilometers\n\nTherefore, Michael rode a total of 860 kilometers in these two periods."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 18/100 path 2/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 18/100 path 2/3 answer='650'
