[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 19/100 start id=gsm8k_test_209
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 19/100 path 1/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 19/100 path 1/3 answer="To calculate the total cost of buying each cup, we first need to determine how many cups were sold at $6000 each. Since there are 12 cups in a dozen, half a dozen would have 12/2 = 6 cups. Therefore, twenty dozen cups would have 20*6 = 120 cups. \n\nNow, let's find out how much the remaining twenty-four cups (half of the forty-eight) cost:\nCost of twenty-four cups = $6000 * 4 = $24000\n\nFinally, to get the total cost of buying each cup, we divide the cost of twenty-four cups by the number of cups:\nTotal cost per cup = $24000 / 120 = $200\n\nSo, the total cost of buying each cup is $200."
