[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 29/100 path 3/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 29/100 path 3/3 answer="To calculate the percentage spent on editing, we first need to find out how long she spent on each task:\n\n1. Writing: 4 hours\n2. Recording: Half of what she wrote, so 4 / 2 = 2 hours\n3. Editing: 90 minutes\n\nNow, let's convert all times to minutes (since they're easier to compare):\n\n1. Writing: 4 hours * 60 minutes/hour = 240 minutes\n2. Recording: 2 hours * 60 minutes/hour = 120 minutes\n3. Editing: 90 minutes\n\nNow, we can sum up these times:\n\nTotal time spent: 240 + 120 + 90 = 450 minutes\n\nFinally, we calculate the percentage of her total work time spent editing:\n\n(Editing time / Total time) * 100 = (90 / 450) * 100 = 0.2 * 100 = 20%\n\nSo, 20% of Carol's total work time was spent editing."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 29/100 done id=gsm8k_test_393 prediction='21.02' gold='20' correct=False vote_counts={'21.02': 1, '20': 1, "To calculate the percentage spent on editing, we first need to find out how long she spent on each task:\n\n1. Writing: 4 hours\n2. Recording: Half of what she wrote, so 4 / 2 = 2 hours\n3. Editing: 90 minutes\n\nNow, let's convert all times to minutes (since they're easier to compare):\n\n1. Writing: 4 hours * 60 minutes/hour = 240 minutes\n2. Recording: 2 hours * 60 minutes/hour = 120 minutes\n3. Editing: 90 minutes\n\nNow, we can sum up these times:\n\nTotal time spent: 240 + 120 + 90 = 450 minutes\n\nFinally, we calculate the percentage of her total work time spent editing:\n\n(Editing time / Total time) * 100 = (90 / 450) * 100 = 0.2 * 100 = 20%\n\nSo, 20% of Carol's total work time was spent editing.": 1}
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 30/100 start id=gsm8k_test_407
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 30/100 path 1/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 30/100 path 1/3 answer="First, let's determine how many steps Elliott took before his jog. We know he walked half of his total steps, so:\n\n\\[ \\text{Steps taken before jog} = \\frac{10,000}{2} = 5,000 \\]\n\nAfter completing his walk to and from school, he took another 1,000 steps. Adding these to his previous steps gives us:\n\n\\[ \\text{Total steps before jog} = 5,000 + 1,000 = 6,000 \\]\n\nFinally, we're told that after his jog, he was left with 2,000 steps remaining. This means:\n\n\\[ \\text{Steps taken after jog} = \\text{Total steps before jog} - 2,000 \\]\n\\[ \\text{Steps taken after jog} = 6,000 - 2,000 = 4,000 \\]\n\nElliott took 4,000 steps during his jog."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 30/100 path 2/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 30/100 path 2/3 answer='To calculate the total number of steps Elliott took during his jog, we can start by considering what he already knew:\n\n- Elliott walked 10,000 steps to and from school.\n- Elliott did another 1,000 steps going with his friend.\n- After jogging for a short walk around the block, he was left with 2,000 steps remaining.\n\nSo, we subtract these from the total steps he needed:\n\nTotal steps taken so far + steps left after jogging = Steps taken during the jog\n\n10,000 (to/from school) + 1,000 (going with friend) - 2,000 (left after jogging) = 9,000 steps\n\nTherefore, Elliott took 9,000 steps during his jog.'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 30/100 path 3/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 30/100 path 3/3 answer='First, we calculate how many steps Elliott took to go to and from school:\n\\[\n\\text{Steps to and from school} = \\frac{\\text{Total steps}}{2} = \\frac{10,000}{2} = 5,000 \\text{ steps}\n\\]\n\nNext, we determine the total number of steps taken including the short jog round:\n\\[\n\\text{Total steps (including jog)} = 1,000 + 5,000 + 2,000 = 8,000 \\text{ steps}\n\\]\n\nElliott started with 10,000 steps and used some to cover the distance of the jogging:\n\\[\n\\text{Steps taken during the jog} = \\text{Total steps} - \\text{Steps before jog} = 8,000 - 2,000 = 6,000 \\text{ steps}\n\\]\n\nTherefore, Elliott took 6,000 steps during his jog.'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 30/100 done id=gsm8k_test_407 prediction="First, let's determine how many steps Elliott took before his jog. We know he walked half of his total steps, so:\n\n\\[ \\text{Steps taken before jog} = \\frac{10,000}{2} = 5,000 \\]\n\nAfter completing his walk to and from school, he took another 1,000 steps. Adding these to his previous steps gives us:\n\n\\[ \\text{Total steps before jog} = 5,000 + 1,000 = 6,000 \\]\n\nFinally, we're told that after his jog, he was left with 2,000 steps remaining. This means:\n\n\\[ \\text{Steps taken after jog} = \\text{Total steps before jog} - 2,000 \\]\n\\[ \\text{Steps taken after jog} = 6,000 - 2,000 = 4,000 \\]\n\nElliott took 4,000 steps during his jog." gold='2000' correct=False vote_counts={"First, let's determine how many steps Elliott took before his jog. We know he walked half of his total steps, so:\n\n\\[ \\text{Steps taken before jog} = \\frac{10,000}{2} = 5,000 \\]\n\nAfter completing his walk to and from school, he took another 1,000 steps. Adding these to his previous steps gives us:\n\n\\[ \\text{Total steps before jog} = 5,000 + 1,000 = 6,000 \\]\n\nFinally, we're told that after his jog, he was left with 2,000 steps remaining. This means:\n\n\\[ \\text{Steps taken after jog} = \\text{Total steps before jog} - 2,000 \\]\n\\[ \\text{Steps taken after jog} = 6,000 - 2,000 = 4,000 \\]\n\nElliott took 4,000 steps during his jog.": 1, 'To calculate the total number of steps Elliott took during his jog, we can start by considering what he already knew:\n\n- Elliott walked 10,000 steps to and from school.\n- Elliott did another 1,000 steps going with his friend.\n- After jogging for a short walk around the block, he was left with 2,000 steps remaining.\n\nSo, we subtract these from the total steps he needed:\n\nTotal steps taken so far + steps left after jogging = Steps taken during the jog\n\n10,000 (to/from school) + 1,000 (going with friend) - 2,000 (left after jogging) = 9,000 steps\n\nTherefore, Elliott took 9,000 steps during his jog.': 1, 'First, we calculate how many steps Elliott took to go to and from school:\n\\[\n\\text{Steps to and from school} = \\frac{\\text{Total steps}}{2} = \\frac{10,000}{2} = 5,000 \\text{ steps}\n\\]\n\nNext, we determine the total number of steps taken including the short jog round:\n\\[\n\\text{Total steps (including jog)} = 1,000 + 5,000 + 2,000 = 8,000 \\text{ steps}\n\\]\n\nElliott started with 10,000 steps and used some to cover the distance of the jogging:\n\\[\n\\text{Steps taken during the jog} = \\text{Total steps} - \\text{Steps before jog} = 8,000 - 2,000 = 6,000 \\text{ steps}\n\\]\n\nTherefore, Elliott took 6,000 steps during his jog.': 1}
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 31/100 start id=gsm8k_test_429
