[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 34/100 start id=gsm8k_test_440
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 34/100 path 1/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 34/100 path 1/3 answer="To find the perimeter of the rectangular bedroom, we can first calculate the width using the formula Area = Length × Width. Given:\nArea = 360 square feet\nLength = 3 yards\n\nWe first convert the length from yards to feet:\n3 yards × 3 feet/yard = 9 feet\n\nNow we substitute these values into the formula:\n360 = 9 × Width\nWidth = 360 ÷ 9 = 40 feet\n\nNow we have both dimensions (length and width):\nLength = 3 yards\nWidth = 40 feet\n\nFinally, we use the formula Perimeter = 2 × (Length + Width) to find the perimeter:\nPerimeter = 2 × (3 + 40)\nPerimeter = 2 × 43\nPerimeter = 86 feet\n\nTherefore, the perimeter of Billie's rectangular bedroom is 86 feet."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 34/100 path 2/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 34/100 path 2/3 answer="To find the perimeter of the room, we first need to determine its width. Since the area of a rectangle is given by the formula `Area = Length x Width`, we can solve for the width:\n\n\\[ 360 \\text{ sq ft} = 3 \\text{ yd} \\times \\text{Width} \\]\n\nSo,\n\n\\[ \\text{Width} = \\frac{\\text{Area}}{\\text{Length}} = \\frac{360}{3} \\text{ yds} = 120 \\text{ yds} \\]\n\nNow that we have both dimensions (length and width), we can calculate the perimeter using the formula `Perimeter = 2 \\times (Length + Width)`:\n\n\\[ \\text{Perimeter} = 2 \\times (3 + 120) \\text{ yds} = 2 \\times 123 \\text{ yds} = 246 \\text{ yds} \\]\n\nTherefore, the perimeter of Billie's rectangular bedroom is 246 yards."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 34/100 path 3/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 34/100 path 3/3 answer='246'
