ial score from Joey's total: \\(240 - 225 = 15\\) points.\nJoey is now 15 points ahead of Marcy.\n\nAnswer: Joey is now winning by \\( \\boxed{15} \\) points.": 1, "To determine by how many points Joey is winning, we first calculate the net increase in points:\nJoey starts with 214 points and gets 26 back, so:\n\\[ \\text{Net Increase} = 214 - 26 = 188 \\]\n\nNext, we look at Marcy's points. We know Marcy started with 225 points and scored 10 more, so:\n\\[ \\text{Final Points} = 225 + 10 = 235 \\]\n\nNow, we find out by how many points Joey is winning by subtracting Marcy's final score from Joey's net increase:\n\\[ \\text{Points Difference} = 188 - 235 = -47 \\]\nSince Joey lost 47 points, he is losing by 47 points compared to Marcy. Therefore, the correct answer is:\n\\[ \\boxed{-47} \\]": 1}
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 36/100 start id=gsm8k_test_449
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 36/100 path 1/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 36/100 path 1/3 answer='To find out how many crayons Beatrice bought in total, we need to calculate the number of crayons from each packet separately and then sum them up:\n\n- For the six packets with eight pieces of color each:\n  \\[ 6 \\text{ packets} \\times 8 \\text{ pieces/packet} = 48 \\text{ pieces} \\]\n\n- For the four packets with sixteen pieces of color each:\n  \\[ 4 \\text{ packets} \\times 16 \\text{ pieces/packet} = 64 \\text{ pieces} \\]\n\nNow, we add these two totals together to get the overall amount:\n\n\\[ 48 \\text{ pieces} + 64 \\text{ pieces} = 112 \\text{ pieces} \\]\n\nBeatrice bought a total of 112 crayons.'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 36/100 path 2/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 36/100 path 2/3 answer='112'
