[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 39/100 start id=gsm8k_test_466
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 39/100 path 1/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 39/100 path 1/3 answer="First, calculate how much each person paid before discounts:\nBecky paid 20 * $0.45 = $<<20*0.45=9>>9.\nKelly paid 20 * $0.50 = $<<20*0.5=10>>10.\n\nNow, calculate how much each paid with their respective discounts:\nBecky's discounted price was $9 - $0.10 = $<<9-0.10=8.90>>8.90.\nKelly's discounted price was $10 - ($10 * 10%) = $10 - $1 = $<<10-1=9>>9.\n\nFinally, find the difference between what Kelly paid and what Becky paid:\n$9 (Kelly) - $8.90 (Becky) = $<<9-8.90=0.10>>0.10 or $1.\n\nKelly paid $1 more than Becky."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 39/100 path 2/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 39/100 path 2/3 answer='101'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 39/100 path 3/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 39/100 path 3/3 answer="First, let's calculate how much Becky paid:\n\nBecky paid 20 apples at 45 cents each:\n20 apples * 45 cents/apple = $90\n\nNext, let's calculate how much Kelly paid:\n\nKelly paid 20 apples at 50 cents each with a 10% discount:\n(100% - 10%) * (20 apples * 50 cents/apple) = 90% * 1000 cents = 900 cents\n20 apples * 50 cents/apple = 1000 cents\n900 cents + 1000 cents = $290\n\nNow, let's find out how much more Kelly paid compared to Becky:\n\n$290 (Kelly's total) - $90 (Becky's total) = $200\n\nSo, Kelly paid $200 more than Becky."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 39/100 done id=gsm8k_test_466 prediction="First, calculate how much each person paid before discounts:\nBecky paid 20 * $0.45 = $<<20*0.45=9>>9.\nKelly paid 20 * $0.50 = $<<20*0.5=10>>10.\n\nNow, calculate how much each paid with their respective discounts:\nBecky's discounted price was $9 - $0.10 = $<<9-0.10=8.90>>8.90.\nKelly's discounted price was $10 - ($10 * 10%) = $10 - $1 = $<<10-1=9>>9.\n\nFinally, find the difference between what Kelly paid and what Becky paid:\n$9 (Kelly) - $8.90 (Becky) = $<<9-8.90=0.10>>0.10 or $1.\n\nKelly paid $1 more than Becky." gold='1' correct=False vote_counts={"First, calculate how much each person paid before discounts:\nBecky paid 20 * $0.45 = $<<20*0.45=9>>9.\nKelly paid 20 * $0.50 = $<<20*0.5=10>>10.\n\nNow, calculate how much each paid with their respective discounts:\nBecky's discounted price was $9 - $0.10 = $<<9-0.10=8.90>>8.90.\nKelly's discounted price was $10 - ($10 * 10%) = $10 - $1 = $<<10-1=9>>9.\n\nFinally, find the difference between what Kelly paid and what Becky paid:\n$9 (Kelly) - $8.90 (Becky) = $<<9-8.90=0.10>>0.10 or $1.\n\nKelly paid $1 more than Becky.": 1, '101': 1, "First, let's calculate how much Becky paid:\n\nBecky paid 20 apples at 45 cents each:\n20 apples * 45 cents/apple = $90\n\nNext, let's calculate how much Kelly paid:\n\nKelly paid 20 apples at 50 cents each with a 10% discount:\n(100% - 10%) * (20 apples * 50 cents/apple) = 90% * 1000 cents = 900 cents\n20 apples * 50 cents/apple = 1000 cents\n900 cents + 1000 cents = $290\n\nNow, let's find out how much more Kelly paid compared to Becky:\n\n$290 (Kelly's total) - $90 (Becky's total) = $200\n\nSo, Kelly paid $200 more than Becky.": 1}
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 40/100 start id=gsm8k_test_469
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 40/100 path 1/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 40/100 path 1/3 answer='4'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 40/100 path 2/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 40/100 path 2/3 answer="First, let's calculate the total number of cupcakes Mary can decorate with all her jars:\n\nEach jar can decorate 8 cupcakes, and there are 6 jars:\n\\( 6 \\text{ jars} \\times 8 \\text{ cupcakes/jar} = 48 \\text{ cupcakes} \\)\n\nMary wants to use up all of her sprinkles for baking, so we'll divide the total number of cupcakes by the cupcake capacity per pan:\n\n\\( 48 \\text{ cupcakes} ÷ 12 \\text{ cupcakes/pan} = 4 \\text{ pans} \\)\n\nTherefore, Mary should bake 4 pans worth of cupcakes."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 40/100 path 3/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 40/100 path 3/3 answer="To determine how many pans worth of cupcakes Mary should bake, we'll follow these steps:\n\n1. Calculate how many cupcakes Mary can decorate with one jar of sprinkles:\n   Each jar decorates 8 cupcakes.\n\n2. Determine how many jars of sprinkles Mary has:\n   Mary has 6 jars of sprinkles.\n\n3. Find out how many cupcakes Mary can decorate with one jar:\n   \\( 8 \\text{ cupcakes/jar} \\times 6 \\text{ jars} = 48 \\text{ cupcakes} \\)\n\n4. Determine how many total cups Mary needs:\n   Mary needs enough cupcakes to make 12 in total (since each pan holds 12).\n\n5. Calculate how many pans worth of cupcakes Mary should bake:\n   Since she can decorate 48 cupcakes with her current supplies and needs 12 in total,\n   \\( \\frac{48 \\text{ cupcakes}}{12 \\text{ cupcakes/pan}} = 4 \\text{ pans} \\)\n\nSo, Mary should bake 4 pans worth of cupcakes to have enough decorations for her total cupcake requirement."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 40/100 done id=gsm8k_test_469 prediction='4' gold='4' correct=True vote_counts={'4': 1, "First, let's calculate the total number of cupcakes Mary can decorate with all her jars:\n\nEach jar can decorate 8 cupcakes, and there are 6 jars:\n\\( 6 \\text{ jars} \\times 8 \\text{ cupcakes/jar} = 48 \\text{ cupcakes} \\)\n\nMary wants to use up all of her sprinkles for baking, so we'll divide the total number of cupcakes by the cupcake capacity per pan:\n\n\\( 48 \\text{ cupcakes} ÷ 12 \\text{ cupcakes/pan} = 4 \\text{ pans} \\)\n\nTherefore, Mary should bake 4 pans worth of cupcakes.": 1, "To determine how many pans worth of cupcakes Mary should bake, we'll follow these steps:\n\n1. Calculate how many cupcakes Mary can decorate with one jar of sprinkles:\n   Each jar decorates 8 cupcakes.\n\n2. Determine how many jars of sprinkles Mary has:\n   Mary has 6 jars of sprinkles.\n\n3. Find out how many cupcakes Mary can decorate with one jar:\n   \\( 8 \\text{ cupcakes/jar} \\times 6 \\text{ jars} = 48 \\text{ cupcakes} \\)\n\n4. Determine how many total cups Mary needs:\n   Mary needs enough cupcakes to make 12 in total (since each pan holds 12).\n\n5. Calculate how many pans worth of cupcakes Mary should bake:\n   Since she can decorate 48 cupcakes with her current supplies and needs 12 in total,\n   \\( \\frac{48 \\text{ cupcakes}}{12 \\text{ cupcakes/pan}} = 4 \\text{ pans} \\)\n\nSo, Mary should bake 4 pans worth of cupcakes to have enough decorations for her total cupcake requirement.": 1}
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 41/100 start id=gsm8k_test_476
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 41/100 path 1/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 41/100 path 1/3 answer='To find out how many books each child got, we first need to determine how many books Sarah bought in total. \n\nGiven:\n- Total amount spent: $300\n- Price of each book: $15\n\nWe can calculate the number of books by dividing the total amount spent by the price per book:\n\nNumber of books = Total amount spent / Price per book\nNumber of books = $300 / $15\nNumber of books = 20\n\nNow, since Sarah gave an equal number of books to her 4 kids, we divide the total number of books by the number of kids:\n\nNumber of books per kid = Number of books / Number of kids\nNumber of books per kid = 20 / 4\nNumber of books per kid = 5\n\nEach child received 5 books.'
