[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 46/100 path 3/3 answer='To calculate the total cost of fruits Verna bought:\n- Apples: 3 × $1.50 = $4.50\n- Oranges: 5 × $0.80 = $4.00\n- Peaches: 6 × $0.75 = $4.50\n\nTotal cost = $4.50 + $4.00 + $4.50 = $13.00\n\nShe gave $20, so the change she received is:\n\nChange = $20 - $13 = $7\n\nTherefore, Verna received $7 in change.'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 46/100 done id=gsm8k_test_542 prediction='8' gold='7' correct=False vote_counts={'8': 2, 'To calculate the total cost of fruits Verna bought:\n- Apples: 3 × $1.50 = $4.50\n- Oranges: 5 × $0.80 = $4.00\n- Peaches: 6 × $0.75 = $4.50\n\nTotal cost = $4.50 + $4.00 + $4.50 = $13.00\n\nShe gave $20, so the change she received is:\n\nChange = $20 - $13 = $7\n\nTherefore, Verna received $7 in change.': 1}
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 47/100 start id=gsm8k_test_546
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 47/100 path 1/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 47/100 path 1/3 answer="To calculate how many letters Elise has written in total, we can break down the process step by step:\n\n1. First, Elise writes each letter individually in full twice.\n   Each letter has 26 letters (since there are 26 letters in the English alphabet). So, writing each letter double is \\(26 \\times 2\\).\n\n2. Then, she writes half of the letters once.\n   Half of the letters in the alphabet is \\(26 \\div 2 = 13\\) letters.\n\n3. Finally, she rewrites all the letters she has already written twice.\n   Since she wrote all 13 letters initially, she writes those again two times, so she writes \\(13 \\times 2\\) letters.\n\nNow, let's calculate:\n1. Writing each letter in full twice: \\(26 \\times 2 = 52\\)\n2. Writing half of the letters: \\(13 \\times 1 = 13\\)\n3. Writing the original letters again twice: \\(13 \\times 2 = 26\\)\n\nAdding these together gives us the total number of letters written:\n\\[52 + 13 + 26 = 91\\]\n\nElise has written a total of 91 letters."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 47/100 path 2/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 47/100 path 2/3 answer='Elise starts with the letter A. She writes down all 26 letters of the alphabet in sequence until she has covered them all. Then, she writes half of the remaining letters (i.e., 13) once each time she finishes writing one letter each time.\n\nSo, before re-writing, she wrote:\n\\[ 26 \\]\n\nAfter she finished writing, she added back half of the remaining letters:\n\\[ 13 + 13 = 26 \\]\n\nTo find out how many letters she wrote in total, we can sum up both parts:\n\\[ 26 (letters written initially) + 26 (letters written twice) = 52 \\]\n\nTherefore, Elise has written a total of 52 letters.'
