[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 50/100 path 1/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 50/100 path 1/3 answer="First, let's determine how old each son is:\n\n- The older son is 12 years old.\n- The younger son is 4 years younger than the older one, so he is 12 - 4 = 8 years old.\n\nNext, we'll calculate how many packs of candles they need:\n\n- For the older son, we divide the number of candles needed (which is half the total price) by the cost per pack:\n  (20 packs * $3/pack) / ($3/5 pack)\n  = 20 * 3 / 3\n  = 20\n\nSo, James needs to buy 20 packs of candles.\n\nFinally, we'll calculate the total cost:\n\n- Each pack costs $3, so 20 packs will cost:\n  20 packs * $3/pack\n  = $60\n\nJames spends $60 on candles for his two sons."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 50/100 path 2/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 50/100 path 2/3 answer="To calculate how much James spends on candles, we first need to determine how many packs he will need to buy for each son:\n\nFor the older son (12 years old), he needs:\n12 / 5 = 2 packs with a remainder of 2 years\n\nFor the younger son (4 years younger than the older one), he needs:\n(4 - 1) / 5 = 3/5 packs (or 0.6 packs)\n\nNow, let's calculate the total number of packs needed:\n2 packs for the older son + 0.6 packs for the younger son = 2.6 packs\n\nSince you can't purchase a fraction of a pack, James would need to round up to the next whole number. So, he will need 3 packs.\n\nEach pack costs $3, so:\n3 packs * $3/pack = $9\n\nTherefore, James will spend $9 on candles."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 50/100 path 3/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 50/100 path 3/3 answer="First, find out how old each son is:\n- The older son is 12 + 4 = 16 years old.\n- The younger son is 16 - 4 = 12 years old.\n\nNext, calculate how many packs of candles James needs to buy:\n- Since he needs 5 candles per pack, he would need 12 / 5 = 2.4 packs.\n- Since he can't buy a fraction of a pack, he will need to round up to 3 packs (since he can't have partial packs).\n\nNow, multiply the number of packs by the cost per pack to get the total amount spent:\n- Cost = 3 packs * $3/pack = $9.\n\nJames spends $9 on candles."
