efore, Gerald had $50 left.": 1, '90': 1}
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 60/100 start id=gsm8k_test_727
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 60/100 path 1/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 60/100 path 1/3 answer='First, calculate the number of windows smashed by the students:\nNumber of windows smashed by students = (64 students * 4 windows/student) * (1/4)\n= 256 windows\n\nThen, calculate the number of windows smashed by the teachers:\nNumber of windows smashed by teachers = (32 teachers * 2 windows/teacher) * (1/4)\n= 160 windows\n\nFinally, sum the number of windows smashed by both groups:\nTotal number of windows smashed = Number of windows smashed by students + Number of windows smashed by teachers\n= 256 + 160\n= 416 windows\n\nTherefore, Hannah smashed a total of 416 windows.'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 60/100 path 2/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 60/100 path 2/3 answer='112'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 60/100 path 3/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 60/100 path 3/3 answer="First, we calculate the number of windows smashed by the students:\n\nFor students' cars:\nEach student's car has 4 windows.\nHannah smashes a quarter of them, so:\n\\( \\frac{1}{4} \\times 64 \\times 4 = 64 \\times \\frac{1}{4} = 16 \\) windows\n\nNext, we calculate the number of windows smashed by the teachers:\n\nFor teachers' cars:\nEach teacher's car has 2 windows.\nHannah smashes a third of them, so:\n\\( \\frac{1}{3} \\times 32 \\times 2 = 32 \\times \\frac{1}{3} = 32 \\times 0.333...\\approx 10 \\) windows\n\nNow, we sum up all the windows smashed by both groups:\n\\( 16 + 10 = 26 \\)\n\nTherefore, Hannah smashed a total of 26 windows."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 60/100 done id=gsm8k_test_727 prediction='First, calculate the number of windows smashed by the students:\nNumber of windows smashed by students = (64 students * 4 windows/student) * (1/4)\n= 256 windows\n\nThen, calculate the number of windows smashed by the teachers:\nNumber of windows smashed by teachers = (32 teachers * 2 windows/teacher) * (1/4)\n= 160 windows\n\nFinally, sum the number of windows smashed by both groups:\nTotal number of windows smashed = Number of windows smashed by students + Number of windows smashed by teachers\n= 256 + 160\n= 416 windows\n\nTherefore, Hannah smashed a total of 416 windows.' gold='112' correct=False vote_counts={'First, calculate the number of windows smashed by the students:\nNumber of windows smashed by students = (64 students * 4 windows/student) * (1/4)\n= 256 windows\n\nThen, calculate the number of windows smashed by the teachers:\nNumber of windows smashed by teachers = (32 teachers * 2 windows/teacher) * (1/4)\n= 160 windows\n\nFinally, sum the number of windows smashed by both groups:\nTotal number of windows smashed = Number of windows smashed by students + Number of windows smashed by teachers\n= 256 + 160\n= 416 windows\n\nTherefore, Hannah smashed a total of 416 windows.': 1, '112': 1, "First, we calculate the number of windows smashed by the students:\n\nFor students' cars:\nEach student's car has 4 windows.\nHannah smashes a quarter of them, so:\n\\( \\frac{1}{4} \\times 64 \\times 4 = 64 \\times \\frac{1}{4} = 16 \\) windows\n\nNext, we calculate the number of windows smashed by the teachers:\n\nFor teachers' cars:\nEach teacher's car has 2 windows.\nHannah smashes a third of them, so:\n\\( \\frac{1}{3} \\times 32 \\times 2 = 32 \\times \\frac{1}{3} = 32 \\times 0.333...\\approx 10 \\) windows\n\nNow, we sum up all the windows smashed by both groups:\n\\( 16 + 10 = 26 \\)\n\nTherefore, Hannah smashed a total of 26 windows.": 1}
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 61/100 start id=gsm8k_test_735
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 61/100 path 1/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 61/100 path 1/3 answer='To find out how many votes candidate C received, we first need to calculate the number of votes each candidate got individually:\n\nCandidate A: 20% of 100 votes = 0.20 * 100 = 20 votes\n\nCandidate B: 50% more than Candidate A = 20 + (0.50 * 20) = 20 + 10 = 30 votes\n\nNow, we know the total number of votes is 100, so we can subtract the votes of Candidates A and B from the total to find out how many votes candidate C had:\n\nVotes for Candidate C = Total votes - Votes for Candidates A and B\nVotes for Candidate C = 100 - 20 - 30 = 50 votes\n\nTherefore, candidate C received 50 votes.'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 61/100 path 2/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 61/100 path 2/3 answer="First, let's find out how many votes each candidate received:\n\nCandidate A: 20% of 100 votes = 0.20 * 100 = 20 votes\n\nCandidate B: 50% more than Candidate A's votes = 20 + (20 * 0.5) = 20 + 10 = 30 votes\n\nNow, we know Candidate A and Candidate B together got 20 + 30 = 50 votes.\n\nTo find out how many votes candidate C got, we subtract the total votes from Candidate A and Candidate B:\n\nVotes for Candidate C = Total votes - (Votes for A + Votes for B)\nVotes for Candidate C = 100 - 50 = 50 votes\n\nSo, candidate C got 50 votes."
