[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 63/100 path 2/3 answer='84.7'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 63/100 path 3/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 63/100 path 3/3 answer='To determine how much money the vendor saves in a week, we first calculate the weekly revenue from selling tomatoes before and after switching vendors.\n\n**Daily Revenue Before Switch:**\nHe sells 500 tomatoes a day at $.5 each.\nRevenue per day = 500 tomatoes/day × $.5/tomato = $25/day\n\n**Weekly Revenue Before Switch:**\nThere are 7 days in a week, so:\nWeekly Revenue = $25/day × 7 days = $175\n\nAfter switching vendors, he sells tomatoes at $.4 each.\n\n**Daily Revenue After Switch:**\nWith the new vendor selling at $.4 each, he now sells 500 tomatoes daily at $0.4 each.\nRevenue per day with new vendor = 500 tomatoes/day × $.4/tomato = $20/day\n\n**Weekly Revenue After Switch:**\nAgain, there are 7 days in a week, so:\nWeekly Revenue with new vendor = $20/day × 7 days = $140\n\n**Savings Per Day:**\nSavings per day = Weekly Revenue with new vendor – Weekly Revenue before switch\n           = $140 – $175\n           = -$35\n\nSince savings per day is negative, it indicates he actually spends more than what he earns each day. To find out the net savings over a week:\n\n**Total Savings Over Week:**\n(Weekly Revenue after switch) × Number of days in a week\n          = $140 × 7 days\n          = $980\n\nTherefore, the total amount of money the vendor saves in a week is **$980**.'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 63/100 done id=gsm8k_test_747 prediction='0.7' gold='350' correct=False vote_counts={'0.7': 1, '84.7': 1, 'To determine how much money the vendor saves in a week, we first calculate the weekly revenue from selling tomatoes before and after switching vendors.\n\n**Daily Revenue Before Switch:**\nHe sells 500 tomatoes a day at $.5 each.\nRevenue per day = 500 tomatoes/day × $.5/tomato = $25/day\n\n**Weekly Revenue Before Switch:**\nThere are 7 days in a week, so:\nWeekly Revenue = $25/day × 7 days = $175\n\nAfter switching vendors, he sells tomatoes at $.4 each.\n\n**Daily Revenue After Switch:**\nWith the new vendor selling at $.4 each, he now sells 500 tomatoes daily at $0.4 each.\nRevenue per day with new vendor = 500 tomatoes/day × $.4/tomato = $20/day\n\n**Weekly Revenue After Switch:**\nAgain, there are 7 days in a week, so:\nWeekly Revenue with new vendor = $20/day × 7 days = $140\n\n**Savings Per Day:**\nSavings per day = Weekly Revenue with new vendor – Weekly Revenue before switch\n           = $140 – $175\n           = -$35\n\nSince savings per day is negative, it indicates he actually spends more than what he earns each day. To find out the net savings over a week:\n\n**Total Savings Over Week:**\n(Weekly Revenue after switch) × Number of days in a week\n          = $140 × 7 days\n          = $980\n\nTherefore, the total amount of money the vendor saves in a week is **$980**.': 1}
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 64/100 start id=gsm8k_test_758
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 64/100 path 1/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 64/100 path 1/3 answer="The amount before the discount is calculated by dividing the marked price by (1 - discount rate), so $140 / (1 - 0.05) = $150. This means the actual cost would be $150. Therefore, you'll pay $150 after applying the 5% discount."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 64/100 path 2/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 64/100 path 2/3 answer='To calculate the amount paid after a 5% discount on a $140 item with a 5% discount, follow these steps:\n\n1. First, find out what 5% of $140 is:\n   (5/100) * $140 = $7\n\n2. Subtract this amount from the original price ($140):\n   $140 - $7 = $133\n\nSo, if a bag is marked at $140 but offers a 5% discount, you will have to pay $133 to cover the cost.'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 64/100 path 3/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 64/100 path 3/3 answer='To calculate the discounted price, we first find the amount of the discount:\n\nDiscount = Marked Price × Percentage Discount\n\nGiven:\nMarked Price (MP) = $140\nPercentage Discount = 5%\n\nTherefore,\nDiscount = $140 × 5%\n= $140 × 0.05\n= $7\n\nNow, subtract the discount from the marked price to get the final price you will pay:\n\nFinal Price = Marked Price - Discount\n= $140 - $7\n= $133\n\nSo, you will have to pay $133 after the discount. The final answer is $133.'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 64/100 done id=gsm8k_test_758 prediction="The amount before the discount is calculated by dividing the marked price by (1 - discount rate), so $140 / (1 - 0.05) = $150. This means the actual cost would be $150. Therefore, you'll pay $150 after applying the 5% discount." gold='133' correct=False vote_counts={"The amount before the discount is calculated by dividing the marked price by (1 - discount rate), so $140 / (1 - 0.05) = $150. This means the actual cost would be $150. Therefore, you'll pay $150 after applying the 5% discount.": 1, 'To calculate the amount paid after a 5% discount on a $140 item with a 5% discount, follow these steps:\n\n1. First, find out what 5% of $140 is:\n   (5/100) * $140 = $7\n\n2. Subtract this amount from the original price ($140):\n   $140 - $7 = $133\n\nSo, if a bag is marked at $140 but offers a 5% discount, you will have to pay $133 to cover the cost.': 1, 'To calculate the discounted price, we first find the amount of the discount:\n\nDiscount = Marked Price × Percentage Discount\n\nGiven:\nMarked Price (MP) = $140\nPercentage Discount = 5%\n\nTherefore,\nDiscount = $140 × 5%\n= $140 × 0.05\n= $7\n\nNow, subtract the discount from the marked price to get the final price you will pay:\n\nFinal Price = Marked Price - Discount\n= $140 - $7\n= $133\n\nSo, you will have to pay $133 after the discount. The final answer is $133.': 1}
