- All other movies are newer.\n   - Total cost of newer movies = \\( 400 \\times 10 = \\$4000 \\)\n\n6. **Add the cost of the older and newer movies to find the total cost:**\n   - Total cost = Cost of newer movies + Cost of old movies\n   - Total cost = \\( 4000 + 800 = \\$4800 \\)\n\nTherefore, the total amount Mike will have to spend on these movies is **$4800**.": 1, "First, let's calculate how many series out of the total number of movies there are:\n\nTotal number of movies = 600\n\nSince a third of the movies are in different series, we have:\n\nNumber of series = Total number of movies / 3\n                       = 600 / 3\n                       = 200\n\nNow, let's subtract the number of series from the total to find out how many regular movies Mike already owns:\n\nRegular movies = Total number of movies - Number of series\n                     = 600 - 200\n                     = 400\n\nNext, let's determine how many old movies are left. Since 40% of the remaining movies are older, we'll first figure out what 40% is of the original number of movies:\n\nPercentage of old movies = 40 / 100\n                           = 0.4\n\nSo, the number of old movies is:\n\nOld movies = Percentage of old movies * Regular movies\n               = 0.4 * 400\n               = 160\n\nFinally, we can calculate the cost of each type of movie and sum them up:\n\nCost of regular movies = Cost of a normal movie * Number of regular movies\n                          = $10 * 400\n                          = $4000\n\nCost of old movies = Cost of a normal movie * Number of old movies\n                      = $10 * 160\n                      = $1600\n\nTotal cost of the replacement movies = Cost of regular movies + Cost of old movies\n                                    = $4000 + $1600\n                                    = $5600\n\nTherefore, the total cost of replacing Mike's movies would be $5600.": 1, '2000': 1}
