[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 75/100 start id=gsm8k_test_939
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 75/100 path 1/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 75/100 path 1/3 answer="Craig and his brother together have spelled out 20 words with 15 letters each, so together they have spelled out \\(20 \\times 15 = 300\\) letters in total before the tenth round.\n\nIn ten rounds, Craig spells out 20 words, meaning he uses up all \\(300 - 20 = 280\\) letters from these two sources.\n\nHis brother spells out words with a total count of letters 50 more than Craig, who spell out 20 letters. Thus, his brother spells out \\(20 + 50 = 70\\) letters in the ten rounds.\n\nTherefore, the total number of letters in the words they've spelled after the ten rounds would be \\(280 + 70 = 350\\)."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 75/100 path 2/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 75/100 path 2/3 answer='Craig spells out 15-letter words 10 times, so he spells out a total of 15 * 10 = 150 words.\nCrisply spells out 15-letter words 1 time, which totals 15 words.\nHis brother spells out words with a total count of letters 50 more than Craig, so he spells out 15 + 50 = 65 letters.\nAdding these together gives Craig and his brother 150 + 65 = 215 letters in total.'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 75/100 path 3/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 75/100 path 3/3 answer="Craig has spelled out 20 words with 15 letters each, so he has spelled out a total of 20 * 15 = 300 letters.\nAfter ten rounds, Craig has spelled out a total of 20 + (10 - 1) * 15 = 20 * 15 + 9 * 15 = 20 * 15 + 9 * 15 = 20 * 15 + 9 * 15 = 300 + 135 = 435 letters.\nIf Craig's brother has spelled words with a total count of letters 50 more than Craig, then his total would be 435 + 50 = 485 letters.\nTherefore, the total number of letters in the words they've spelled after the ten rounds is 435 + 485 = 920 letters."
