[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 76/100 path 1/3 answer="To determine the total number of children in the drill, we'll consider how many children are in each group:\n1. There are 5 schools, so there are \\(5 \\times 8 = 40\\) children standing on one side of the row.\n2. Since there are 7 rows, there are also 7 groups (because \\(7\\) rows make up \\(7\\) groups).\n\nSo, the total number of children will be \\(40 + 7 \\times 5\\), because there’s an additional group with 5 children at the end.\n\nTherefore, the calculation would be:\n\n\\[40 + (7 \\times 5) = 40 + 35 = 75\\]\n\nHence, the total number of children who can participate in the mass drills is **75**."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 76/100 path 2/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 76/100 path 2/3 answer='To find out how many children can be in the drill, we multiply the number of rows by the number of schools per row:\n\nNumber of children = Number of rows × Number of schools per row\n\nGiven:\nNumber of rows = 7\nNumber of schools per row = 5\n\nSo,\n\nNumber of children = 7 × 5 = 35\n\nTherefore, there can be 35 children in the drill.'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 76/100 path 3/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 76/100 path 3/3 answer='35'
