[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 77/100 start id=gsm8k_test_946
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 77/100 path 1/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 77/100 path 1/3 answer="We know that if Sam had 70 loaves of bread last Friday, then the number of loaves he has now can be calculated using the formula: \\( \\text{Number of loaves} = 7 \\times \\text{Last Friday's loaves} - 40 \\). Given that the number of loaves he has now is 40 less than seven times the number he had last Friday, we substitute the values into the equation:\n\n\\[ 70 = 7 \\times 70 - 40 \\]\n\nSolving for 70:\n\n\\[ 70 + 40 = 7 \\times 70 \\]\n\\[ 110 = 7 \\times 70 \\]\n\nTherefore, the bakery currently has 110 loaves of bread."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 77/100 path 2/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 77/100 path 2/3 answer="First, let's determine how many loaves of bread the bakery originally had. Since the number of loaves the bakery has is equal to seven times the number of loaves Sam had minus 40 (because it has 40 less than that), we can express this relationship with the equation:\n\n\\[ \\text{Number of loaves} = 7 \\times (\\text{Sam's loaves}) - 40 \\]\n\nGiven that Sam had 70 loaves last Friday, we plug in that value into our equation:\n\n\\[ \\text{Bakery's loaves} = 7 \\times 70 - 40 \\]\n\\[ \\text{Bakery's loaves} = 490 - 40 \\]\n\\[ \\text{Bakery's loaves} = 450 \\]\n\nSo, the bakery originally had 450 loaves of bread."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 77/100 path 3/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 77/100 path 3/3 answer="First, calculate seven times the number of loaves Sam originally had:\n7 * 70 = 490\n\nThen subtract the 40 fewer loaves from Sam's total:\n490 - 40 = 450\n\nSo, the bakery has 450 loaves of bread."
