s} = 25 \\text{ ounces/box} \\times 16 \\text{ ounces/package} = 400 \\text{ ounces} \\]\n\nFinally, we convert the total weight of the boxes from ounces to pounds:\n\\[ \\text{Total weight of boxes} = 400 \\text{ ounces} \\div 16 \\text{ ounces/pound} = 25 \\text{ pounds} \\]\n\nSo the total weight of the crayons and the boxes when there are 16 ounces to a pound is 25 pounds.': 1, '12.5': 1, 'First, we calculate how many groups of crayons Nik can make with 200 crayons:\n\\[ \\text{Number of crayon groups} = \\frac{200}{8} = 25 \\]\n\nNext, we find out how many boxes are needed for these crayon groups. Since each group requires 1 box:\n\\[ \\text{Number of boxes} = 25 \\]\n\nEach box weighs 8 ounces. Therefore, the total weight of the crayons is:\n\\[ \\text{Weight of crayons} = 25 \\times 8 = 200 \\text{ ounces} \\]\n\nConverting the crayon weight from ounces to pounds (since 1 pound = 16 ounces):\n\\[ \\text{Weight of crayons in pounds} = \\frac{200 \\text{ ounces}}{16 \\text{ ounces/pound}} = 12.5 \\text{ pounds} \\]\n\nSo, the total weight of the crayons and the boxes is:\n\\[ \\boxed{12.5} \\]': 1}
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 85/100 start id=gsm8k_test_1140
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 85/100 path 1/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 85/100 path 1/3 answer="To determine how many potatoes Gomer ate, we'll break down the problem into smaller steps:\n\n1. First, find out how many scoops of mashed potatoes Gomer ate:\n   \\[\n   5 \\text{ less than } 23 = 23 - 5 = 18 \\text{ scoops}\n   \\]\n\n2. Next, find out how many potatoes are needed to make those 18 scoops:\n   \\[\n   \\frac{18}{6} = 3 \\text{ potatoes}\n   \\]\n\n3. Now, calculate how many potatoes are left when each potato makes \\( \\frac{3}{6} = 0.5 \\) scoops (since making one scoop requires 3 potatoes):\n   \\[\n   \\frac{18}{0.5} = 36 \\text{ potatoes}\n   \\]\n\nThus, Gomer ate a total of \\( \\boxed{36} \\) potatoes."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 85/100 path 2/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 85/100 path 2/3 answer="To find out how many potatoes Gomer ate, we first need to calculate how many potatoes he consumed based on the number of scoops and the relationship between them.\n\nFrom the information given:\n- Gomer ate 5 less than 23 scoops of mashed potatoes.\n- It takes 3 less than 6 potatoes to make 1 less than 3 scoops of mashed potatoes.\n\nLet's break down each part:\n\n1. Scoop calculation:\n   23 (total scoops) - 5 = 18 scoops\n\n2. Potatoes calculation:\n   Since it takes 3 less than 6 potatoes to make 1 less than 3 scoops:\n   6 (potato needed per scoop) - 3 (less potatoes needed per scoop)\n   = 3 potatoes needed per scoop\n\nNow, using these calculations:\n- Number of potatoes Gomer ate: 18 scoops * 3 potatoes/scoop = 54 potatoes\n\nSo, Gomer ate 54 potatoes."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 85/100 path 3/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 85/100 path 3/3 answer="To find out how many potatoes Gomer ate, let's break down the problem step-by-step:\n\n1. First, we need to determine how many scoops of mashed potatoes Gomer ate. According to the information given:\n   - Gomer ate 5 less than 23 scoops.\n   - This can be calculated as: 23 - 5 = 18 scoops.\n\n2. Next, we'll figure out how many potatoes Gomer needed. According to the second part of the problem:\n   - It takes 3 less than 6 potatoes to make 1 less than 3 scoops.\n   - This can be calculated as: (6 - 3) / 3 = 1 potato.\n\n3. Finally, we add up all these values to get the total number of potatoes Gomer ate:\n   - Total potatoes eaten = scoops + potatoes per scoop\n   - Total potatoes eaten = 18 (scoops) + 1 (potatoes per scoop) = 19 potatoes\n\nTherefore, Gomer ate 19 potatoes."
