[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 86/100 path 2/3 answer='To calculate how much Jen spends on food in the month of May, we first need to determine how many days there are in May, and then multiply that number by the amount of money they need for food per day.\n\nMay has 31 days. Each fish needs $1 worth of food per day. So, the total cost for all the fish in May would be:\n\n\\[ 3 \\text{ fish/day} \\times \\$1/\\text{fish/day} \\times 31 \\text{ days} = \\$93 \\]\n\nTherefore, Jen spends $93 on food in the month of May.'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 86/100 path 3/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 86/100 path 3/3 answer='To calculate how much Jen spends on fish food for May, we first need to determine how many fish she gets. Since she gets 3 fish and eats them every day, we can divide the number of fish by the number of days in May to find out how many days it takes for all the fish to be eaten. There are 31 days in May. Then we multiply the total number of fish by the daily consumption rate to get the total amount spent. \n\nCalculation:\nNumber of days = Number of fish ÷ Number of fish/day = 3 ÷ 31 ≈ 0.098 (approximately) \nTotal cost for fish = Number of fish × Daily consumption rate = 3 × $1 = $3\n\nTherefore, Jen spends approximately $3 on food for all the fish in May.'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 86/100 done id=gsm8k_test_1149 prediction='30' gold='93' correct=False vote_counts={'30': 1, 'To calculate how much Jen spends on food in the month of May, we first need to determine how many days there are in May, and then multiply that number by the amount of money they need for food per day.\n\nMay has 31 days. Each fish needs $1 worth of food per day. So, the total cost for all the fish in May would be:\n\n\\[ 3 \\text{ fish/day} \\times \\$1/\\text{fish/day} \\times 31 \\text{ days} = \\$93 \\]\n\nTherefore, Jen spends $93 on food in the month of May.': 1, 'To calculate how much Jen spends on fish food for May, we first need to determine how many fish she gets. Since she gets 3 fish and eats them every day, we can divide the number of fish by the number of days in May to find out how many days it takes for all the fish to be eaten. There are 31 days in May. Then we multiply the total number of fish by the daily consumption rate to get the total amount spent. \n\nCalculation:\nNumber of days = Number of fish ÷ Number of fish/day = 3 ÷ 31 ≈ 0.098 (approximately) \nTotal cost for fish = Number of fish × Daily consumption rate = 3 × $1 = $3\n\nTherefore, Jen spends approximately $3 on food for all the fish in May.': 1}
