[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 87/100 path 2/3 answer="First, let's determine how much land Abraham bought with the initial sale. He initially owned 80 square meters out of which half was sold for $50 each. So, the total amount from the first sale is:\n\n\\[ \\frac{80}{2} \\times \\$50 = \\$40 \\times \\$50 = \\$2000 \\]\n\nNext, we calculate how much he got from the second sale. He sold \\( \\frac{1}{4} \\) of the original land at $30 each:\n\n\\[ \\frac{1}{4} \\times 80 \\times \\$30 = 20 \\times \\$30 = \\$600 \\]\n\nAfter the first two sales, the remaining land is:\n\n\\[ 80 - 40 - 600 = \\$200 \\]\n\nNow, he sold the remaining land for $3 per square meter. Since he has \\( \\frac{1}{4} \\) of his original land left, the area of this remaining land is \\( \\frac{1}{4} \\times 80 = 20 \\) square meters. Therefore, the earnings from selling this portion of the land is:\n\n\\[ 20 \\times \\$3 = \\$60 \\]\n\nAdding up all the earnings, we get:\n\n\\[ \\$200 + \\$60 = \\$260 \\]\n\nSo, Abraham will be able to earn **$260** after selling all his unused land."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 87/100 path 3/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 87/100 path 3/3 answer='First, we calculate how much land he sold:\n\nHalf of the 80 square meters is:\n80 / 2 = 40 square meters\n\nThen we subtract the amount sold from the original land to find out what he still has left:\n80 - 40 = 40 square meters\n\nNext, we calculate how much he sold the first time at $50 each:\n40 x $50 = $<<40*50=2000>>2000\n\nAfterward, we calculate how much he sold the second time at $30 each:\n(40 - 40) x $30 = $<<0 x 30=0>>\n\nFinally, we add up all the amounts to find out how much money he will have:\n$2000 + $0 = $<<2000+0=2000>>2000\n\nTherefore, Abraham can earn $2000 after selling all his unused land.'
