[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 92/100 path 3/3 answer="First, we calculate how many grapes Madeline’s brother used to make each glass:\nMadeline used 6 grapes, and her brother made 5 times as many, so he used 6 * 5 = 30 grapes per glass.\n\nNext, we subtract the number of grapes used by Madeline’s brother from the total number of grapes:\nTotal grapes - Madeline's brother's grapes = Remaining grapes.\n12 (total) - 30 = -18\n\nHowever, since we can't have negative grapes, it seems like there might be a mistake or misunderstanding here. Let's re-examine:\n\nWe know they ended up with 12 grapes per pie. So, if they made 4 pies, they would have needed 12 * 4 = 48 grapes in total.\n\nBut our calculation shows they had only 18 grapes left. This implies we may have misunderstood something about the recipe or the initial conditions given.\n\nIf they made 4 pies, and each pie requires 12 grapes, then the total number of grapes required for all pies should be 12 * 4 = 48 grapes.\n\nGiven that they started with 6 grapes (which was 12 - 6), they actually had no excess, meaning they didn’t end up with any extra grapes beyond what they started with.\n\nSince we're looking for the initial amount of grapes, but we found out they had none left after making pies, I'll provide the final correct interpretation based on these calculations:\n\nThey started with 0 grapes, ending up with 18 grapes instead. Since they couldn't have had any, this implies they either didn't start with enough grapes or their initial condition for making pies wasn't met. But typically, when someone starts with zero and ends up with some, they haven't eaten any grapes yet.\n\nSo, if we adjust the question"
