[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 93/100 path 2/3 answer="First, let's find out how many marbles Brendan lost when he tripped over the pebble:\n\nHalf of the 10 marbles he had initially were lost:\n(1/2) * 10 = 5 marbles\n\nBrendan also found 3 marbles when he searched for them later.\n\nSo, the total number of marbles he had before coming across the beads was:\nInitial marbles + Lost marbles + Found marbles\n= 10 (initial) + 5 (lost) + 3 (found)\n= 18 marbles\n\nWhen he went back home, one of the marbles was discarded because it wasn't a marble. So we subtract 1 from the total count:\n\nTotal marbles Brendan ended up with = Marbles before finding or discarding + Marbles found or discarded\n= 18 + 1\n= 19 marbles\n\nTherefore, Brendan ended up with 19 marbles."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 93/100 path 3/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 93/100 path 3/3 answer="To determine how many marbles Brendan ended up with, let's follow these steps:\n\n1. **Initial Marbles**: Brendan started with 10 marbles.\n2. **Marbles Dropped**: He tripped over a pebble and dropped half of the marbles.\n   \\[\n   \\text{Half} = \\frac{10}{2} = 5 \\text{ marbles}\n   \\]\n3. **Marbles Left After Drop**: Subtract the number of marbles he dropped from the initial amount.\n   \\[\n   10 - 5 = 5 \\text{ marbles}\n   \\]\n4. **Remaining Marbles After Scratching**: After dropping half of his marbles, he found 3 marbles.\n   \\[\n   \\text{Remaining} = 5 - 3 = 2 \\text{ marbles}\n   \\]\n5. **Beads Found**: Brendan also found one of the remaining marbles to be a bead.\n   \\[\n   2 + 1 = 3 \\text{ marbles}\n   \\]\n\nSo, Brendan ended up with 3 marbles.\n\nAnswer: \\(\\boxed{3}\\)"
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 93/100 done id=gsm8k_test_1247 prediction='4' gold='7' correct=False vote_counts={'4': 1, "First, let's find out how many marbles Brendan lost when he tripped over the pebble:\n\nHalf of the 10 marbles he had initially were lost:\n(1/2) * 10 = 5 marbles\n\nBrendan also found 3 marbles when he searched for them later.\n\nSo, the total number of marbles he had before coming across the beads was:\nInitial marbles + Lost marbles + Found marbles\n= 10 (initial) + 5 (lost) + 3 (found)\n= 18 marbles\n\nWhen he went back home, one of the marbles was discarded because it wasn't a marble. So we subtract 1 from the total count:\n\nTotal marbles Brendan ended up with = Marbles before finding or discarding + Marbles found or discarded\n= 18 + 1\n= 19 marbles\n\nTherefore, Brendan ended up with 19 marbles.": 1, "To determine how many marbles Brendan ended up with, let's follow these steps:\n\n1. **Initial Marbles**: Brendan started with 10 marbles.\n2. **Marbles Dropped**: He tripped over a pebble and dropped half of the marbles.\n   \\[\n   \\text{Half} = \\frac{10}{2} = 5 \\text{ marbles}\n   \\]\n3. **Marbles Left After Drop**: Subtract the number of marbles he dropped from the initial amount.\n   \\[\n   10 - 5 = 5 \\text{ marbles}\n   \\]\n4. **Remaining Marbles After Scratching**: After dropping half of his marbles, he found 3 marbles.\n   \\[\n   \\text{Remaining} = 5 - 3 = 2 \\text{ marbles}\n   \\]\n5. **Beads Found**: Brendan also found one of the remaining marbles to be a bead.\n   \\[\n   2 + 1 = 3 \\text{ marbles}\n   \\]\n\nSo, Brendan ended up with 3 marbles.\n\nAnswer: \\(\\boxed{3}\\)": 1}
