[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 99/100 path 1/3 answer="To find out how long it took Vanessa to complete her part of the race, we need to determine her speed first. Since Aaron runs each mile twice as fast as Vanessa, and he completes his part in 16 minutes, his speed is:\n\n\\[ \\text{Aaron's speed} = \\frac{16 \\text{ minutes}}{1 \\text{ mile}} \\times 2 = 24 \\text{ minutes/mile} \\]\n\nVanessa can run twice as far as Aaron, so:\n\n\\[ \\text{Vanessa's distance} = 2 \\times (24 \\text{ minutes/mile}) = 48 \\text{ miles} \\]\n\nNow, to find out how long it takes Vanessa to complete her 48-mile segment, we use her current speed:\n\n\\[ \\text{Vanessa's time} = \\frac{\\text{Distance}}{\\text{Speed}} = \\frac{48 \\text{ miles}}{24 \\text{ minutes/mile}} = 2 \\text{ minutes} \\]\n\nSo, Vanessa took 2 minutes to complete her part of the race."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 99/100 path 2/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 99/100 path 2/3 answer='First, calculate the time it took Aaron to run one mile, since he runs twice as fast as Vanessa. Since Vanessa ran 4 miles and Aaron runs twice as fast, Aaron takes \\( \\frac{4}{2} = 2 \\) minutes to run one mile. \n\nNext, determine the total time taken by both to complete their respective distances. Aaron took 16 minutes to run his distance. Since Aaron runs twice as fast as Vanessa, his speed multiplier is 2. Therefore, if Vanessa took 4 minutes to run one mile, Aaron would have taken \\( 16 \\times 2 = 32 \\) minutes to do the same distance. \n\nNow, we know that Vanessa took 4 minutes to run 4 miles, so she took \\( \\frac{4}{4} = 1 \\) minute to run one mile. Thus, Vanessa took \\( 16 \\times 1 = 16 \\) minutes to complete her part of the race. \n\nSo, Vanessa took 16 minutes to complete her part of the race.'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 99/100 path 3/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 99/100 path 3/3 answer="First, we calculate Aaron's speed:\n\\[ \\text{Aaron's speed} = 2 \\times \\text{Vanessa's speed} = 2 \\times \\frac{\\text{Vanessa's distance}}{\\text{Time}} \\]\n\nGiven that Vanessa ran 4 miles and it took her 16 minutes, we can find her speed:\n\\[ \\text{Vanessa's speed} = \\frac{\\text{distance}}{\\text{time}} \\]\n\\[ \\text{Vanessa's speed} = \\frac{4\\text{ miles}}{16\\text{ minutes}} \\]\n\nNow, since Aaron runs each mile twice as fast as Vanessa:\n\\[ \\text{Aaron's speed} = 2 \\times \\text{Vanessa's speed} \\]\n\nTo find out how long it takes for Aaron to complete one mile, we use the same formula with Aaron's speed and the number of miles he needs to cover (which is also equal to his time):\n\\[ \\text{Aaron's time to complete one mile} = \\frac{\\text{distance}}{\\text{speed}} \\]\n\\[ \\text{Aaron's time to complete one mile} = \\frac{4}{\\text{Aaron's speed}} \\]\n\nFinally, to find out how long it takes for Vanessa to complete 4 miles:\n\\[ \\text{Vanessa's time to complete 4 miles} = \\frac{4}{\\text{Vanessa's speed}} \\]\n\nLet's plug in the values:\n\n1. Vanessa's speed calculation:\n\\[ \\text{Vanessa's speed} = \\frac{4}{16}\\text{ minutes/mile} = 0.25\\text{ minutes/mile} \\]\n\n2. Aaron's speed:\n\\[ \\text{Aaron's speed} = 2 \\times 0."
