h to complete their respective distances. Aaron took 16 minutes to run his distance. Since Aaron runs twice as fast as Vanessa, his speed multiplier is 2. Therefore, if Vanessa took 4 minutes to run one mile, Aaron would have taken \\( 16 \\times 2 = 32 \\) minutes to do the same distance. \n\nNow, we know that Vanessa took 4 minutes to run 4 miles, so she took \\( \\frac{4}{4} = 1 \\) minute to run one mile. Thus, Vanessa took \\( 16 \\times 1 = 16 \\) minutes to complete her part of the race. \n\nSo, Vanessa took 16 minutes to complete her part of the race.': 1, "First, we calculate Aaron's speed:\n\\[ \\text{Aaron's speed} = 2 \\times \\text{Vanessa's speed} = 2 \\times \\frac{\\text{Vanessa's distance}}{\\text{Time}} \\]\n\nGiven that Vanessa ran 4 miles and it took her 16 minutes, we can find her speed:\n\\[ \\text{Vanessa's speed} = \\frac{\\text{distance}}{\\text{time}} \\]\n\\[ \\text{Vanessa's speed} = \\frac{4\\text{ miles}}{16\\text{ minutes}} \\]\n\nNow, since Aaron runs each mile twice as fast as Vanessa:\n\\[ \\text{Aaron's speed} = 2 \\times \\text{Vanessa's speed} \\]\n\nTo find out how long it takes for Aaron to complete one mile, we use the same formula with Aaron's speed and the number of miles he needs to cover (which is also equal to his time):\n\\[ \\text{Aaron's time to complete one mile} = \\frac{\\text{distance}}{\\text{speed}} \\]\n\\[ \\text{Aaron's time to complete one mile} = \\frac{4}{\\text{Aaron's speed}} \\]\n\nFinally, to find out how long it takes for Vanessa to complete 4 miles:\n\\[ \\text{Vanessa's time to complete 4 miles} = \\frac{4}{\\text{Vanessa's speed}} \\]\n\nLet's plug in the values:\n\n1. Vanessa's speed calculation:\n\\[ \\text{Vanessa's speed} = \\frac{4}{16}\\text{ minutes/mile} = 0.25\\text{ minutes/mile} \\]\n\n2. Aaron's speed:\n\\[ \\text{Aaron's speed} = 2 \\times 0.": 1}
