[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][mmlu] sample 24/100 path 1/3 answer="To find the correct values, we need to use the relationships between these physical properties:\n\n1. Ionization Energy (IE): \\( IE = \\frac{1}{n} \\times \\text{energy required to remove one electron from a neutral atom}\\)\n   - For Na: \\( IE = 1s^2 \\rightarrow 1s^2 2s^2 2p^6 3s^2 3p^6 \\)\n   - Given: \\( IE = 496 \\, \\text{kJ/mol} \\)\n\n2. Atomic Radius (R): \\( R = \\sqrt{\\frac{Z^2}{\\gamma}} \\), where \\( Z \\) is the atomic number and \\( \\gamma \\) is the effective nuclear charge\n\nLet's calculate the values step by step:\n\nFor Sodium:\n- Atomic Number (\\( Z \\)): 11\n- Effective Nuclear Charge (\\( \\gamma \\)) = \\( Z + 1 \\approx 11 + 1 = 12 \\)\n\nUsing the formula:\n\\[ R = \\sqrt{\\frac{Z^2}{\\gamma}} \\]\n\\[ R = \\sqrt{\\frac{11^2}{12}} \\]\n\\[ R = \\sqrt{\\frac{121}{12}} \\]\n\\[ R = \\sqrt{10.0833} \\]\n\\[ R \\approx 3.16 \\, \\text{pm} \\]\n\nNow, using the ionization energy formula:\n\\[ IE = \\frac{1}{n} \\times \\text{ionization energy per electron} \\]\nwhere \\( n = 1s^2 \\)\n\\[ 496 \\, \\text{kJ/mol} = \\frac{1}{1s^2} \\times \\text{ionization energy per electron} \\]"
