[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][mmlu] sample 35/100 path 2/3 answer="To solve this problem, we need to manipulate the given equations to isolate variables and then use them to find \\( |a + b + c| \\).\n\nGiven:\n\\[ a(a + 2b) = \\frac{104}{3}, \\]\n\\[ b(b + 2c) = \\frac{7}{9}, \\]\n\\[ c(c + 2a) = -7. \\]\n\nFirst, let's simplify each equation:\n\n### Simplify \\( a(a + 2b) = \\frac{104}{3} \\)\n\\[ a^2 + 2ab = \\frac{104}{3}. \\]\n\n### Simplify \\( b(b + 2c) = \\frac{7}{9} \\)\n\\[ b^2 + 2bc = \\frac{7}{9}. \\]\n\n### Simplify \\( c(c + 2a) = -7 \\)\n\\[ c^2 + 2ac = -7. \\]\n\nNow, let's try to combine these simplified equations to see if they can help us find a relationship between \\( a, b, \\) or \\( c \\). Let's multiply both sides of \\( c(c + 2a) = -7 \\) by 3 to align it with the first equation:\n\n\\[ 3c(c + 2a) = -21. \\]\n\nThis gives us:\n\n\\[ 3c^2 + 6ac = -21. \\]\n\nNotice that this is very similar to our current equation \\( b^2 + 2bc = \\frac{7}{9} \\):\n\n\\[ 3c^2 + 6ac = (3c)^2 + 6ac. \\]\n\nBy comparing coefficients, we see:\n\n\\[ 3c^2 + 6ac = 3c^2 + 6ac"
