[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][mmlu] sample 37/100 path 3/3 answer='To determine the correct option, let\'s analyze each statement in context of perfect competition:\n\n**Statement A**: "Average revenue is less than price at all levels of output."\n\nIn perfect competition, firms face no fixed costs and can sell their product at the market price (i.e., \\(P = \\text{price} = R\\)). This means that the price (\\(R\\)) remains constant regardless of production volume. Therefore, the average revenue (\\(\\frac{\\text{Price}}{\\text{Quantity}}\\)) is also always less than the market price, making this statement true in perfect competition.\n\n**Statement B**: "Marginal revenue is equal to marginal cost at all levels of output."\n\nWhile in perfect competition, firms have no fixed costs, they do incur variable costs. Marginal revenue represents the additional revenue generated from selling one more unit, which includes both the incremental revenue and the variable costs. As long as there are no fixed costs, the relationship between marginal revenue and marginal cost will change depending on the level of output. It is possible for marginal revenue to be greater or equal to marginal cost at certain levels, but it cannot be equal under normal circumstances because of diminishing returns.\n\n**Statement C**: "Price and marginal revenue are equal at all levels of output."\n\nThis is generally false in perfect competition because the price (\\(P\\)) depends on the quantity produced (\\(Q\\)), and while marginal revenue (\\(MR\\)) is related to \\(Q\\) through the marginal cost function, it does not necessarily equate \\(P\\) when producing infinitely many units.\n\n**Statement D**: "It is the same as the market demand curve."\n\nIn perfect competition, the demand curve reflects market conditions where all prices and quantities are determined by supply and demand. However, since market equilibrium occurs where price equals marginal cost, the market demand curve is derived from these equations and is different from what would be used'
