[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][mmlu] sample 75/100 path 1/3 answer='To determine how the court should rule on these motions, let\'s analyze each one based on the information provided:\n\n1. **Sentence 1**: "Every element of a group generates a cyclic subgroup of the group."\n   - This statement suggests that the group (in this case, the tavern) can generate a cyclic subgroup under certain conditions, which might not necessarily be true if the premises are false. However, since we don\'t have specific details about the premise being false or not true, we\'ll assume this statement is relevant but not conclusive on its own.\n\n2. **Sentence 2**: "The symmetric group \\(S_{10}\\) has 10 elements."\n   - This statement is straightforward; the symmetric group \\(S_{10}\\) indeed has 10 elements.\n\nNow, considering the two sentences:\n- Sentence 1 suggests the existence of cyclic subgroups, which is generally assumed to hold in many cases when discussing groups.\n- Sentence 2 specifically mentions the number of elements in \\(S_{10}\\), stating it has 10 elements. \n\nGiven these points, the correct interpretation is that both sentences are true, but they are presented separately. Since the question asks about ruling on these motions and assuming both sentences are true, the most appropriate conclusion would be to grant both motions.\n\n**Final Answer:** C. Grant the tavernÕs motion, because there is no evidence that the tavern breached a duty to the man.'
