[zero_shot][qwen2_5_1_5b_instruct][mmlu] sample 17/100 done id=mmlu_validation_206 prediction='To determine which statements about the class of ARIMA(p,d,q) models are true, let\'s analyze each statement one by one:\n\n(i) The "I" stands for integrated.\n- This statement is false because "I" actually stands for "Integrated," not "Independent." In time series analysis, "I" refers to differencing the data to make it stationary.\n\n(ii) An ARIMA(p,1,q) model estimated on a series of logs of prices is equivalent to an ARIMA(p,0,q) model estimated on a set of continuously compounded returns.\n- This statement is true. Logarithmic transformations can help stabilize variance and achieve stationarity, making it easier to estimate an ARIMA model. Continuously compounded returns also lead to a stationary process through their properties.\n\n(iii) It is plausible for financial time series that the optimal value of d could be 2 or 3.\n- This statement is true. Financial time series often exhibit non-stationary behavior due to mean reversion or other dynamics. The order of integration (d) can range from -p to q, allowing for flexibility depending on the specific characteristics of the data.\n\n(iv) The estimation of ARIMA models is incompatible with the notion of cointegration.\n- This statement is' gold='A' correct=False
