[zero_shot][qwen2_5_1_5b_instruct][mmlu] sample 26/100 done id=mmlu_validation_350 prediction="To determine which type of function grows the slowest, we need to compare their growth rates as N approaches infinity.\n\n1. **O(N)**: This represents linear growth, where the function increases at a rate proportional to N.\n2. **O(N^(1/2))**: This represents square root growth, where the function increases at a rate proportional to the square root of N.\n3. **O(N^(1/4))**: This represents fourth root growth, where the function increases at a rate proportional to the fourth root of N.\n4. **O(N^(1/N))**: This represents N raised to the power of 1 over N, which simplifies to 1/N^N, indicating exponential decay.\n\nAs N becomes very large, the term with the highest exponent will dominate the growth rate. Therefore:\n\n- **O(N) has the fastest growth** because it's linear.\n- **O(N^(1/2)) has slower growth than O(N) but faster than O(N^(1/4)).**\n- **O(N^(1/4)) has slower growth than O(N^(1/2)) but faster than O(1/N).**\n- **O(N^(1/N)) has the slowest growth** because it decays" gold='C' correct=False
