[zero_shot][qwen2_5_1_5b_instruct][mmlu] sample 36/100 done id=mmlu_validation_476 prediction="To solve this problem, we need to find the derivative of \\( f(x) \\), which represents the slope of the tangent line at any point \\( x \\). Then, we will set this derivative equal to the slope of the secant line over the interval [0,1].\n\nStep 1: Find the derivative of \\( f(x) = e^x - x^2 \\).\n\\[ f'(x) = \\frac{d}{dx}(e^x - x^2) = e^x - 2x \\]\n\nStep 2: Calculate the slope of the secant line over the interval [0,1].\nThe secant line's slope can be found using the formula for the average rate of change between two points.\n\\[ m_{\\text{sec}} = \\frac{f(1) - f(0)}{1 - 0} \\]\n\\[ f(1) = e^1 - 1^2 = e - 1 \\]\n\\[ f(0) = e^0 - 0^2 = 1 \\]\nSo,\n\\[ m_{\\text{sec}} = \\frac{(e-1) - 1}{1} = e - 2 \\approx 0.7" gold='B' correct=False
