[zero_shot][qwen2_5_1_5b_instruct][mmlu] sample 69/100 done id=mmlu_validation_1140 prediction="Step 1: Understand the nature of the transaction.\nThe shipping company sells a boat and leases it back under a sale-leaseback arrangement. This means that the boat remains owned by the shipping company but is used as collateral for a loan or financing agreement with the leasing company.\n\nStep 2: Consider the impact on accounting treatment.\nIn an asset swap like this, the accounting treatment depends on how the assets are classified and whether there is a change in control. Since the boat is still owned by the shipping company, it would typically remain classified as property, plant, and equipment (PP&E) of the shipping company.\n\nStep 3: Analyze each option.\nA. The boat will not be classified in property, plant and equipment of the shipping company.\n   - Incorrect. The boat should continue to be classified as PP&E of the shipping company because it remains their asset despite being leased out.\n\nB. The shipping company will recognize the total profit on the sale of the boat in the current year.\n   - Incorrect. In a sale-leaseback, the profit recognition is deferred until the lease ends and the boat is returned to the seller. There's no immediate recognition of profits.\n\nC. The shipping company will not recognize depreciation expense for the boat in the current year" gold='D' correct=False
