[zero_shot][qwen2_5_1_5b_instruct][mmlu] sample 70/100 done id=mmlu_validation_1149 prediction="To determine how much of the long-term capital loss Decker can deduct, we need to follow these steps:\n\n1. **Calculate Decker's adjusted basis at the end of the year**: \n   - Initial basis = $25,000\n   - Ordinary income = $10,000\n   - Long-term capital loss = $4,000\n   - Adjusted basis = Initial basis + Ordinary income - Long-term capital loss\n   - Adjusted basis = $25,000 + $10,000 - $4,000 = $31,000\n\n2. **Determine the maximum deductible loss**:\n   - Under Section 1221(a) of the Internal Revenue Code, the maximum deduction allowed for long-term capital losses is equal to the lesser of (a) the taxpayer's net long-term capital gain from all sources for the taxable year or (b) the total amount of long-term capital losses carried forward from previous years.\n\n3. **Check if there is any net long-term capital gain**:\n   - Since Decker does not have any other capital gains during the year, there is no net long-term capital gain.\n\n4. **Apply" gold='C' correct=False
