[self_consistency][qwen2_5_1_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 2/100 path 2/3 answer="To determine how long it takes Tom to get back from point 1 to point 4, we need to calculate his total distance traveled and divide it by his speed.\n\nFirst, let's find the total distance:\n\n- From 1 to 4 PM (first leg): \\( d_1 \\) miles\n- Back from 4 PM to 1 PM (second leg): \\( d_2 \\) miles\n\nGiven:\n- Speed going: \\( v_1 = 10 \\) mph\n- Speed returning: \\( v_2 = 6 \\) mph\n\nSince we don't have the exact distances \\( d_1 \\) and \\( d_2 \\), but we know they sum up to the total time spent traveling, we can use the following relationship:\n\n\\[ T_{total} = t_1 + t_2 \\]\n\nWhere:\n- \\( T_{total} \\) is the total time taken.\n- \\( t_1 \\) is the time for the first trip.\n- \\( t_2 \\) is the time for the return trip.\n\nWe also know that:\n\n\\[ d_1 = v_1 \\times t_1 \\]\n\\[ d_2 = v_2 \\times t_2 \\]\n\nCombining these equations gives us:\n\n\\[ T_{total} = v_1 \\times t_1 + v_2 \\times t_2 \\]\n\nHowever, since we're given the speeds and asked about the time difference, we can simplify our approach by considering the relative times rather than specific distances.\n\nIf the problem implies equal distribution of time between going out and coming back (without assuming equal durations on each trip):\n\n- Half the time for departure would go into the outbound journey.\n- The other half would go into the return journey.\n\nHence, if we consider the average or midpoint time for both legs (which simplifies our calculation"
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_1_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 2/100 path 3/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_1_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 2/100 path 3/3 answer="Tom's journey consists of two parts:\n1. Travel from 1 to 4 PM at a speed of 10 mph.\n2. Travel back from 4 to 12 PM at a speed of 6 mph.\n\nFor the first part (from 1 to 4 PM):\nDistance = Speed × Time\nTime = Distance ÷ Speed\nSince we don't know the distance yet, let's call it D. So,\nD = 10 × T1\n\nWhere T1 is the time taken for the first part of the journey.\n\nNow, for the second part (from 4 to 12 PM):\nD = 6 × T2\n\nWhere T2 is the time taken for the second part of the journey.\n\nWe know that the total time for both journeys should sum up to the total time available between 1 and 12 PM, which is 11 hours minus the time spent on the first part. Let's denote the time spent on the first part as T1 and the time spent on the second part as T2.\n\nT1 + T2 = Total Time Available - Time Spent on First Part\n\nSubstituting the values, we get:\n\n11 - T1 + T2 = 11 - T1\n\nSimplifying,\n\nT2 = T1\n\nNow, since they cover the same distance but with different speeds,\n\nD = 10 × T1 = 6 × T1\n\nDividing both sides by T1 gives us:\n\n10 = 6\n\nTherefore, T1 = 6 / 10 = 0.6 hours\n\nSo, Tom spends 0.6 hours traveling from 1 to 4 PM and another 0.6 hours traveling back from 4 to 12 PM.\n\nTotal time taken by Tom to travel back:\n\nT2 = 0.6"
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_1_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 2/100 done id=gsm8k_test_51 prediction='1' gold='5' correct=False vote_counts={'1': 1, "To determine how long it takes Tom to get back from point 1 to point 4, we need to calculate his total distance traveled and divide it by his speed.\n\nFirst, let's find the total distance:\n\n- From 1 to 4 PM (first leg): \\( d_1 \\) miles\n- Back from 4 PM to 1 PM (second leg): \\( d_2 \\) miles\n\nGiven:\n- Speed going: \\( v_1 = 10 \\) mph\n- Speed returning: \\( v_2 = 6 \\) mph\n\nSince we don't have the exact distances \\( d_1 \\) and \\( d_2 \\), but we know they sum up to the total time spent traveling, we can use the following relationship:\n\n\\[ T_{total} = t_1 + t_2 \\]\n\nWhere:\n- \\( T_{total} \\) is the total time taken.\n- \\( t_1 \\) is the time for the first trip.\n- \\( t_2 \\) is the time for the return trip.\n\nWe also know that:\n\n\\[ d_1 = v_1 \\times t_1 \\]\n\\[ d_2 = v_2 \\times t_2 \\]\n\nCombining these equations gives us:\n\n\\[ T_{total} = v_1 \\times t_1 + v_2 \\times t_2 \\]\n\nHowever, since we're given the speeds and asked about the time difference, we can simplify our approach by considering the relative times rather than specific distances.\n\nIf the problem implies equal distribution of time between going out and coming back (without assuming equal durations on each trip):\n\n- Half the time for departure would go into the outbound journey.\n- The other half would go into the return journey.\n\nHence, if we consider the average or midpoint time for both legs (which simplifies our calculation": 1, "Tom's journey consists of two parts:\n1. Travel from 1 to 4 PM at a speed of 10 mph.\n2. Travel back from 4 to 12 PM at a speed of 6 mph.\n\nFor the first part (from 1 to 4 PM):\nDistance = Speed × Time\nTime = Distance ÷ Speed\nSince we don't know the distance yet, let's call it D. So,\nD = 10 × T1\n\nWhere T1 is the time taken for the first part of the journey.\n\nNow, for the second part (from 4 to 12 PM):\nD = 6 × T2\n\nWhere T2 is the time taken for the second part of the journey.\n\nWe know that the total time for both journeys should sum up to the total time available between 1 and 12 PM, which is 11 hours minus the time spent on the first part. Let's denote the time spent on the first part as T1 and the time spent on the second part as T2.\n\nT1 + T2 = Total Time Available - Time Spent on First Part\n\nSubstituting the values, we get:\n\n11 - T1 + T2 = 11 - T1\n\nSimplifying,\n\nT2 = T1\n\nNow, since they cover the same distance but with different speeds,\n\nD = 10 × T1 = 6 × T1\n\nDividing both sides by T1 gives us:\n\n10 = 6\n\nTherefore, T1 = 6 / 10 = 0.6 hours\n\nSo, Tom spends 0.6 hours traveling from 1 to 4 PM and another 0.6 hours traveling back from 4 to 12 PM.\n\nTotal time taken by Tom to travel back:\n\nT2 = 0.6": 1}
