[self_consistency][qwen2_5_1_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 19/100 path 3/3 answer="Let's denote the number of dozens of cups as \\( C \\) and the price per dozen cups as \\( P_c \\). The cost of one cup would then be \\( \\frac{P_c}{12} \\).\n\nFrom the problem statement:\n\\[ C \\cdot P_c = \\$1200 \\]\n\\[ \\text{Cost of half a dozen plates} = \\frac{1}{2} \\cdot 6000 = \\$3000 \\]\n\nWe also know that:\n\\[ C \\cdot \\frac{P_c}{12} = \\$3000 - 1200 \\]\n\nSubstituting \\( C \\cdot \\frac{P_c}{12} \\) with the expression from the first equation:\n\\[ \\frac{12 \\cdot (\\$3000 - 1200)}{C} = \\$3000 \\]\n\\[ \\frac{\\$3600}{C} = \\$3000 \\]\n\\[ C = \\frac{\\$3600}{\\$3000} = 1.2 \\]\n\nSince \\( C \\) represents dozens of cups, the actual number of cups is \\( 1.2 \\times 12 = 14.4 \\), but since we can't have a fraction of a cup, let's consider whole numbers. We'll solve it again carefully without rounding:\n\nGiven:\n\\[ 12 \\cdot \\frac{P_c}{12} = \\$3000 - 1200 \\]\n\\[ \\frac{P_c}{12} = \\$1800 \\]\n\\[ P_c = 1800 \\times 12 \\]\n\\[ P_c = \\$21600 \\]\n\nSo,\n\\[ C \\cdot P_c = 12"
