[self_consistency][qwen2_5_1_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 24/100 path 2/3 answer='Let \\( B \\) represent the number of boys and \\( G \\) represent the number of girls. Given:\n\\[ B = 30 \\]\n\\[ G = 3B \\]\n\nFirst, calculate the number of girls:\n\\[ G = 3 \\times 30 = 90 \\]\n\nNext, let \\( N \\) represent the number of non-gendered children. According to the problem, there are \\(\\frac{1}{10}\\) as many non-gendered children as boys:\n\\[ N = \\frac{1}{10}B \\]\n\nSubstitute \\( B \\) with 30:\n\\[ N = \\frac{1}{10} \\times 30 = 3 \\]\n\nNow, find the total number of children by summing the number of boys, girls, and non-gendered children:\n\\[ Total = B + G + N \\]\n\nSubstitute the values we found:\n\\[ Total = 30 + 90 + 3 \\]\n\nCalculate the sum:\n\\[ Total = 123 \\]\n\nTherefore, the total number of children in the classroom is 123.'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_1_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 24/100 path 3/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_1_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 24/100 path 3/3 answer='123'
