[self_consistency][qwen2_5_1_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 78/100 path 2/3 answer="Let's denote:\n- \\( S \\) as the number of small stuffed animals,\n- \\( L \\) as the number of large stuffed animals.\n\nFrom the problem statement, we know:\n1. The cost of each small stuffed animal is $4.\n2. The total earnings are $120.\n3. Teresa sold twice as many small stuffed animals as large ones.\n\nWe can set up the following equations based on these facts:\n\n\\[ 4S + 3L = 120 \\]\n\\[ S = 2L \\]\n\nFirst, substitute \\( S = 2L \\) into the first equation:\n\n\\[ 4(2L) + 3L = 120 \\]\n\\[ 8L + 3L = 120 \\]\n\\[ 11L = 120 \\]\n\\[ L = \\frac{120}{11} \\approx 10.91 \\]\n\nSince the number of stuffed animals must be a whole number, let’s check if there was a mistake or rounding issue. Given the constraints, it seems likely there might have been a miscalculation in interpreting the exact values.\n\nRevisiting the calculations with exact division:\n\n\\[ 11L = 120 \\]\n\\[ L = \\frac{120}{11} \\approx 10.91 \\]\n\nGiven this result, let's re-evaluate the interpretation:\n- If \\( L = 10.91 \\), then \\( S = 2L \\approx 21.82 \\).\n\nHowever, since numbers of items sold must be integers, let's assume the closest integer solution fitting both conditions.\n\nConsidering practical constraints:\n- If \\( L = 11 \\), then \\( S = 2 \\times 11 = 22 \\).\n- Check if \\("
