[self_consistency][qwen2_5_1_5b_instruct][mmlu] sample 24/100 path 1/3 answer='Use the given values to calculate the second ionization energy using the formula:\n\n\\[ \\text{Second Ionization Energy} = \\text{First Ionization Energy} - \\frac{\\text{Atomic Mass}}{(\\text{Atomic Radius})^2} \\]\n\nGiven:\n- First Ionization Energy (I1) = 496 kJ/mol\n- Atomic Radius (r) = 186 pm = \\(1.86 \\times 10^{-10}\\) m\n- Atomic Mass ≈ 23 g/mol = \\(23 \\times 10^{-3}\\) kg/mole\n\nConvert masses to kilograms per cubic meter:\n- I1 = \\(496 \\times 10^3\\) J/kg·m³\n- r² = \\((1.86 \\times 10^{-10})^2\\) = \\(3.4596 \\times 10^{-20}\\) m²\n\nSubstitute into the equation:\n\\[ \\text{Second Ionization Energy} = 496 \\times 10^3 - \\frac{(23 \\times 10^{-3})(3.4596 \\times 10^{-20})}{(1.86 \\times 10^{-10})^2} \\]\n\\[ = 496 \\times 10^3 - \\frac{79.0628 \\times 10^{-23}}{3.4596 \\times 10^{-20}} \\]\n\\[ = 496 \\times 10^3 - 2.28 \\times 10^{-2} \\]\n\\[ = 496 \\times 10^3 - 0.228 \\]\n\\[ ='
