[self_consistency][qwen2_5_1_5b_instruct][mmlu] sample 35/100 path 2/3 answer="We start with the given equations:\n\n\\[\na(a+2b) = \\frac{104}{3}, \\quad b(b+2c) = \\frac{7}{9}, \\quad c(c+2a) = -7\n\\]\n\nFirst, let's express these equations in a more convenient form:\n\n\\[\n3a^2 + 6ab = 104, \\quad 9b^2 + 18bc = 7, \\quad 9c^2 + 18ca = -63\n\\]\n\nNext, we need to solve these equations simultaneously. We can try to eliminate one variable at a time. Let's start by eliminating \\(b\\) from the first two equations:\n\nMultiply the first equation by 3:\n\n\\[\n9a^2 + 18ab = 304\n\\]\n\nNow subtract the second equation from this result:\n\n\\[\n(9a^2 + 18ab) - (9b^2 + 18bc) = 304 - 7\n\\]\n\nSimplify:\n\n\\[\n9a^2 - 9b^2 + 18ab - 18bc = 297\n\\]\n\nFactor out common terms:\n\n\\[\n9(a^2 - b^2) + 18(ab - 2bc) = 297\n\\]\n\nDivide everything by 9:\n\n\\[\na^2 - b^2 + 2(ab - 2bc) = 33\n\\]\n\nThis simplifies further to:\n\n\\[\n(a - b)(a + b) + 2(ab - 2bc) = 33\n\\]\n\nNext, we need another approach to directly solve for \\(a + b + c\\). Let’s consider solving each equation separately or combining"
